s":["English: locative name from either of two places called Troutbeck (Westm and Cumb)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Troutbeck was born in 1355, in Plemstall, Cheshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Lady Isabel de Warrington. He died in 1445, in Dunham on the Hill, Cheshire, England, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1355–1445":"1355–1445","1341–1397":"1341–1397","1382–1447":"1382–1447","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1355":"1355","1397":"1397","1341":"1341","1382":"1382","Plemstall, Cheshire, England":"Plemstall, Cheshire, England","Dunham on the Hill, Cheshire, England":"Dunham on the Hill, Cheshire, England","Trafford Bridge, Plemstall, Cheshire, England":"Plemstall, Cheshire, England","Warrington, Lancashire, England":"Warrington,